description:
I was not impressed by the food, everything was pretty bland and some things seemed to be not so fresh. In addition, there was an invasion of fruit flies - it was so disgusting. They were everywhere, buzzing in front of our faces, landing on our food, plates, chopsticks, and drowning in our glasses and the black vinegar sauce for the dumplings. If it hadn't been a friend's birthday dinner I would have walked out right away. There must have been hundreds, my seat neighbor and I killed a combined total of at least 30 - we lost count at some point - and didn't even make a dent in the swarm surrounding us. It is beyond me why the owner decided to keep the restaurant open besides such an obvious and disgusting insect problem, especially since the place wasn't exactly busy. There was our table and I think two or three other smaller tables were occupied, otherwise it was empty.

The food (I didn't do the ordering, so some names may be vague):

Walnut shrimp: bland and starchy/slimy; walnuts were good;

Salt and pepper shrimp: bland but otherwise ok - at least for the first few bites; didn't want to continue eating it after multiple flies had landed on the plate;

Soup dumplings: the top of them was too chewy or almost hard, like it dried out before steaming. The soup inside was pretty flavorless and the meat felt grainy, the texture was definitely off. 

Beef chow mein: The beef had a weird sponge-like texture, noodles were greasy, not very well flavored;

Chinese broccoli: this dish actually seemed fresh and was ok if slightly overcooked.

Siu mai: again, flavorless and weird grainy meat texture;

The owner seemed apologetic about the flies and brought us complimentary steamed buns, but that in no way redeems such a huge hygiene problem and mediocre-to-bad food - sorry. The quality of  the food was nowhere close to what I have had at other places in the Richmond and Sunset. I guess I have to keep going there.
